\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec3 A Handmade Web
\f1\b0 \
\
The term 'handmade' usually refers to objects made by hand or by using simple tools rather than machines. The result may be homely \'97 as in a child's clay ashtray \'97 or exquisite \'97 as in a pair of bespoke brogues.\
\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f0\b \cf0 I evoke the term 'handmade web' to refer to web pages coded by hand rather than by software; web pages made and maintained by individuals rather than by businesses or corporations; web pages which are provisional, temporary, or one-of-a-kind; web pages which challenge conventions of reading, writing, design, ownership, privacy, security, or identity.
\f1\b0 \
\
Handmade web pages flourished in the mid-to-late-1990s, in the brief period after the academic web and before the corporate web. \'91Handmade\'92 is by no means the only or best term to define the web of this period.\
\
In her essay,\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://art.teleportacia.org/observation/vernacular/"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 \strokec4 A Vernacular Web}}\'a0(2005), Olia Lialina describes the web of the mid-1990s as:\
bright, rich, personal, slow and under construction. It was a web of sudden connections and personal links. Pages were built on the edge of tomorrow, full of hope for a faster connection and a more powerful computer... it was a web of amateurs soon to be washed away by dot.com ambitions, professional authoring tools and guidelines designed by usability experts.\
For more information on Olia Lialina and Dragan Espenschied's excellent research on the amateur web, see:\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://contemporary-home-computing.org/1tb/about"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 \strokec4 One Terabyte of Kilobyte Age: Digging through the Geocities Torrent}}.\
\

\f0\b I evoke the term 'handmade web' in order to make a correlation between handmade web pages and handmade print materials, such as zines, pamphlets, and artists books.
\f1\b0 \
\
I made my first web-based work in 1995. The impetus for\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://luckysoap.com/butterflies/parasite.html"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 \strokec4 Fishes & Flying Things}}\'a0came from the material practices of fine art and book-making. The text evolved from an installation art exhibition I had on at the time. From this text, I created a small book-work which was meant to tell a circular story but when people got to the end they stopped reading because that\'92s the way books work. In the web version, the last page linked to the first; the story circled round and round. Of the installation, no physical evidence remains. Of the book-work, only one copy. The QuarkExpress file is stored on a 44 MB SyQuest cartridge which I still own, but the contents of which I can no longer access. The handmade website, on the other hand, is still online and it still works.\
\
The handmade web emerged at a time when print and digital enjoyed a more symbiotic relationship. This is evident in the early output of the\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://tracearchive.ntu.ac.uk/index.asp"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 \strokec4 trAce Online Writing Centre}}\'a0founded at Nottingham Trent University in 1995. Over the next decade trAce evolved into one of the most influential online writing communities in the world. trAce\'92s first output was a\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://tracearchive.ntu.ac.uk/writersforthefuture/1995/"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 \strokec4 word-processed photocopied booklet}}\'a0which contained links to websites distributing journals and zines. Fittingly, trAce\'92s last output was also a print booklet, in which it is stated:\
The trAce community embraced both camps, and some early chatlogs contain lively discussions about the use of mixed media in writing\'85 The creative hypertexts and hypermedia in the trAce Archive can easily be compared to the multifarious pages of an artist\'92s book. (PDF\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://tracearchive.ntu.ac.uk/traces/traces.pdf"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 \strokec4 trAces: A Commemoration of Ten Years of Artistic Innovation at trAce}}, page 14)\
One of the many interesting things about the\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://tracearchive.ntu.ac.uk/index.asp"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 \strokec4 online archive}}\'a0of the trAce Online Writing Centre is how much it reflects the context of the creation and dissemination of its contents. Whereas archives held in museums or libraries generally contain artifacts created elsewhere \'97 manuscripts illuminated in a monastery, for example, or photographs developed in a darkroom \'97 the handmade web pages contained in this online archive continue to exist in the medium within which they were created. That said, the frames through which we view them continue to change.\
\
In "Media Archaeology: Method and Machine versus History and Narrative of Media" (2011) Wolfgang Ernst observes: "If a radio from a museum collection is reactivated to play broadcast channels of the present, it changes its status: it is not a historical object anymore but actively generates sensual and informational presence." Similarly, when viewing old web pages in modern browsers we are confronted with a temporal paradox. Layer upon layer of\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://tracearchive.ntu.ac.uk/cyberfest/index.htm"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 \strokec4 dated web-design aesthetics}}\'a0overlap and peel like wallpaper, revealing earlier versions beneath. Pages optimised for lower resolutions now take\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://tracearchive.ntu.ac.uk/frame5/"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 \strokec4 less than a third of the screen}}. Ghosts of browsers past mingle with occasional page errors, dead links, and missing images. Sound files play automatically. Warnings abound, issued from earlier eras, addressed to readers who are not us.\
\
For example, M.D. Coverley\'92s\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://tracearchive.ntu.ac.uk/frame5/coverley/index.html"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 \strokec4 The Personalization of Complexity}}\'a0(2001) "explores the ways in which each of our personal computers have become idiosyncratic, individualized entities, only sometimes manageable by the owners." Fittingly, the piece itself warns that it is viewable only on Level 4 and 5 Microsoft Internet Explorer and Level 4 Netscape. Netscape 6 will not support many of the features in this essay.\
\
These are not artifacts of a dead web but rather, signposts on a map of a living web pointing to a web as it once was, a web in progress, a web in the making.\
\

\f0\b I evoke the term 'handmade web' in order to advocate for an ongoing active engagement with the making of web pages and of web policies.
\f1\b0 \
\
In\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://dashes.com/anil/2012/12/the-web-we-lost.html"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 \strokec4 The Web We Lost}}\'a0(2012), Anil Dash writes: "In the early days of the social web, there was a broad expectation that regular people might own their own identities by having their own websites, instead of being dependent on a few big sites to host their online identity."\
\
In February 2015 the online journal QUARTZ published an article with the provocative headline:\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://qz.com/333313/milliions-of-facebook-users-have-no-idea-theyre-using-the-internet/"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 \strokec4 Millions of Facebook users have no idea they\'92re using the internet}}. As the article states: "This is more than a matter of semantics. The expectations and behaviors of the next billion people to come online will have profound effects on how the internet evolves."\
\
In October 2014 the online journal GIZMODO published an article heralding\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://gizmodo.com/the-great-web-1-0-revival-1651487835"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 \strokec4 The Great Web 1.0 Revival}}. Its author Kyle Chayka observed:\
The booming size of today's mainstream social networks and the constant level of noise we have to deal with has inspired a sudden return to a time when the internet was quieter, safer, and more intimate\'85 We're nostalgic for the close-knit, DIY nature of the early web, where everything was smaller...\
The DIY aesthetics and practices of the mid-1990s have been embraced by the anti-social network\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://tilde.club/"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 \strokec4 TILDE.CLUB}}, which hosts a small community of users on a single unix computer. For some, TILDE.CLUB serves as a platform for revisiting amateur web aesthetics in a contemporary context. For example, on her page, Olia Lialina invites users to view a new net art work\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://tilde.club/~olialia/"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 \strokec4 640x480}}\'a0- a 4-tab browser installation. For many others however, TILDE.CLUB has served as little more than a hip territory to occupy. Many pages remain blank.\
\
