\f0\b \cf0 I evoke the term 'handmade web' in order to draw attention both to the manual labour involved in the composition of web pages, and the functioning of the web page itself as a 'manual', a 'handbook', a set of instructions required for a computer program to run.
\f1\b0 \
\
For most of its history web pages have been read on desktop or laptop computers. Readers have had the option of right-clicking on any page, selecting View Page Source, copying, pasting, and re-writing the source code. In this manner, readers become writers.\
\
In February 2015, Matthew Rothberg created a website called\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://github.com/mroth/unindexed"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 \strokec4 Unindexed}}\'a0which continuously searched Google for itself. It survived for 22 days before being indexed, at which point it was permanently deleted. Rothberg has since shared the\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://github.com/mroth/unindexed"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 \strokec4 source code on GitHub}}, so you too can create a website which self-destructs the moment Google indexes it.\
\
Dozens of readers have re-written the source code of Nick Montfort\'92s\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://nickm.com/poems/taroko_gorge.html"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 \strokec4 Taroko Gorge}}\'a0(2008). For many, this was their first experience 'making' a computer-generated text.\
\
I have rewritten\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://nickm.com/poems/taroko_gorge.html"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 \strokec4 Taroko Gorge}}\'a0three times. Further to the close relation between the handmade web and ephemeral print materials, excerpts of output and source code from the first iteration,\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://luckysoap.com/generations/gorge.html"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 \strokec4 Gorge}}\'a0(2010), were published in my very small press print book\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://luckysoap.com/generations/generations.html"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 \strokec4 GENERATION[S]}}\'a0(2010), which, I believe, is now only available as a PDF.\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://luckysoap.com/generations/gorge.html"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 \strokec4 Gorge}}\'a0is a never-ending tract of computer-generated text spewing verse approximations, poetic paroxysms on food, consumption, decadence, and desire.\
\

\f0\b I evoke the term 'handmade web' in order to draw attention to the physical body.
\f1\b0 \
\
Consider the manual labour carried out by the mouse hand in Daniel Eatock's\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.onemilescroll.com/"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 \strokec4 The One Mile Scroll}}\'a0(2008) A few entries appear at the top of the screen - Denver, The Mile High City - my grandfather\'92s grave, Denver - after that we scroll and scroll. The hand is made to work. Through the labour of the body the virtual space of the browser window is transformed into an actual, physical distance.\
\
Ironically, handheld devices have distanced us from the handmade web. In\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://theliteraryplatform.com/2014/08/from-the-digital-to-the-bookbound/"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 \strokec4 Reading Writing Interfaces: From the Digital to the Bookbound}}\'a0(2014), Lori Emerson argues: "The iPad works because users can\'92t know how it works" (15). Reading the web on an iPhone, iPad, or similar device, readers do not have the option of viewing the page source. The iPad provides consumers with access to materials created by others, but cannot easily be used as a tool in the handcrafting of new materials.\
\

\f0\b I evoke the term 'handmade web' to suggest slowness and smallness as a forms of resistance.
\f1\b0 \
\
In today's highly commercialised web of multinational corporations, proprietary applications, read-only devices, search algorithms, Content Management Systems, WYSIWYG editors, and digital publishers it becomes an increasingly radical act to hand-code and self-publish experimental web art and writing projects.\
\
The more proprietary, predatory, and puerile a place the web becomes, the more committed I am to using it in poetic and intransigent ways.\
\
J. R. Carpenter, March 2015.}